</FIGURE></P>
<P><PB N="37" REF="39">
Court. Call another witne&s;s.&mdash;[Duncan Buchanan &s;worn.]</P>
<P>D. Buchanan. On Jan. 13, 1740-1, the captain ordered the barge and yawl up (meach of which was a mid&s;hipman) and ordered a mid&s;hipman and &s;ix of the bargemen to go to the White Hart, the Foot of the College green. That when they came there, they &s;aw the Captain, Mahony, and five of the Privateer's, who were drinking hot Flip in a room by them&s;elves, whil&s;t him&s;elf and the five bargemen were &s;itting in the public kit|chen drinking of ale. That &s;hortly after he &s;aw &s;ir John come from mr. Smith's, oppo&s;ite the White Hart, where his man was waiting for him, with pi&s;tols to each of their hor&s;es: That the Privateer's men &s;eeing him, they ru&s;hed out together, and were for &s;eizing &s;ir John then; but the Captain ordered them not to touch him at that time, but to follow him, and &s;ee which way he went. That they followed him round the corner, and the Cap|tain after them; but the captain returned to the White Hart again in about an hour, and ordered the boat down.&mdash;That on the &s;un|day following, the &s;ame gentleman he &s;aw in the Green was brought on board the Ruby: That as he was bringing on board, the Capt. bid the people not mind what he &s;aid, for he was a madman; but he would bring him to his &s;en&s;es by and by. That he &s;aw no more of him at that time. That at twelve o'clock he was placed centry over &s;ir John, and a little after the Capt. &s;ent his man for him:
<PB N="38" REF="40">
That he gave the centry at the gun-room charge, that nobody &s;hould come down the ladder 'till he had &s;poke with the Captain. That when he went into the Captain's cabin, he &s;aw the Captain and Mahony with a bottle of Rum and a gla&s;s before them, out of which he had a dram. That the Captain a&s;ked him, If his brother made any noi&s;e? On which he told him, That he made a little moan the time he was there. The Captain replied, I know the rea&s;on of that, he wants to be &s;hifted: I will come down and &s;hift him with dry &s;tockings pre&s;ently. That when he went out, the C$ptain told him to let nobody into the cabin to &s;ir John but Mahony. Says Mahony, You may let ano|ther go, becau&s;e&mdash;here he &s;topped. About two, the Captain came down, and a&s;ked him, If his brother made any noi&s;e? and li&s;tened him&s;elf at the cabin door. Then the Capt. &s;aid to him, Centry, give me the &s;word, and you go upon deck; becau&s;e I want to talk to my brother privately: That accordingly he gave him the &s;word, and went up into the gun-room, and there walked. That a little while after down came Mahony, and the Centry a&s;ked, Where he was going? He &s;aid, D&mdash;n you, you dog, what is that to you? D&mdash;n you, how bu&s;y you make your&s;elf! That then Mahony went down into the cock|plt, and &s;o into the Pur&s;er's cabin. That &s;oon after, he heard &s;ir John mutter out, Murder! Then every thing was quiet for a little while, and the Captain took the lan|thorn
<PB N="39" REF="41">
that was hanging up, and gave it into the cabin him&s;elf. That &s;eeing the candle given into the cabin, he thought it not pro|per for the Captain to &s;tand without a light, and therefore lighted a candle in the gun|room, and was going down into the cockpit, where the Captain was &s;tanding with a &s;word in his hand; but on his approach the Capt. held the &s;word to his brea&s;t, &s;aying, Stay where you are, That accordingly he went back, and walked for a &s;mall time in the gun|room: That the Captain came to the foot of the ladder with the candle out, telling him to light it and come down: which he accordingly did. Then the Captain gave him the &s;word, and bid him take his po&s;t; locking and bolting the cabin door, and put|ting the key in his pocket (which before the murder was left in the door;) telling him, If he heard his brother make any more noi&s;e, to &s;end to him and let him know it.</P>
<P>Theodore Cote, ma&s;ter of the Ruby, de|clar'd, He &s;aw the gentleman brought on board, and the &s;hip was then in King's Road. That in the morning the Captain &s;ent for him, and told him, he had an order from the Ad|miralty to go to &s;ea, though he did not care if he got no farther than the Holmes; and a&s;ked him, If there was good anchoring ground there? Mr. Cote replied, There was no &s;uch thing as anchoring there. The Captain in&s;i&s;ted very much on going, but I told him, The &s;hip was an old tattered ve&s;&s;el,
<PB N="40" REF="42">
and that he mu&s;t go again&s;t wind and tide: So I did not care to venture to move the &s;hip from where &s;he was.</P>
<Q>[Then there aro&s;e a di&s;pute, whether the Ship was really in the Liberties of the city and county of Bri&s;tol; the Captain endeavouring to prove, that &s;he rode a good way up the Severn. But &s;everal of the olde&s;t officers being &s;worn, and depo&s;ing that they had for many years &s;er|ved Proce&s;&s;es out of the courts of Bri&s;tol and We&s;tmin&s;ter in King's Road, it proved a &s;ufficient pre|cedent to confirm the authority of the Court.]</Q>
<P>Mr. Williams &s;wore, That he &s;teered the Barge &s;ir John was carried down in, and heard a great deal of talk, the &s;ub&s;tance of which is before recited by the other Evidence; particularly that part of it, where &s;ir John advi&s;ed the Captain, after he had murdered him to go and hang him&s;elf, &amp;c.</P>
<P>Mr. Weller, the carpenter, proved that he put the bolts upon the Pur&s;er's cabin door, by the Captain's order, whil&s;t &s;ir John was in the cabin.</P>
<P><PB N="41" REF="43">
William M'Ginnis &s;wore, That he &s;aw the Captain &s;tand at the Pur&s;er's cabin door, at the time of the murder, with a drawn &s;word in his hand; and that when he offered to draw near him, the Captain held up his &s;word, and bid him keep back.</P>
<P>Mr. Duggen, doctor's mate, That the Captain ordered him into the cabin to &s;eel the gentleman's pul&s;e, and that he acquaint|ed the Captain that his pul&s;e was regular.</P>
<P>The Captain in his defence pleaded the ut|mo&s;t innocence; alledging, That could it be thought he could be guilty of the murder of his brother, whereas by his death he lo&s;t at lea&s;t 40,00 l.?&mdash;That fickne&s;s and di&s;|order in the pri&s;on, debarred him of his law|yer and friends conver&s;ing with him.&mdash;That he applied to the Captain of the Ruby as &s;oon as he was allowed pen, ink, and paper, for his evidences on &s;hip board (which were lieutenant Perry; the doctor; mr. Robert Haythorn, mr. Richard Wil&s;on, and Hugh Di&s;cal:)&mdash;That he applied to the lords of the admiralty, who &s;ent him an order, but that the &s;hip &s;ailed the day before it arrived: which debarred him of ju&s;tifying him&s;elf, they being material evidences:&mdash;That the News Papers being full of reflecting fal&s;e expre&s;&s;ions, was a great detriment to him:&mdash;Then he urged (in a low &s;peech) That his pro&s;ecutors would &s;et ea&s;y in the birth right of his innocent children, &s;hould he be convicted:&mdash;In vindication of &s;eizing &s;ir John in that manner, he urge$$, That he
<PB N="42" REF="44">
was a lunatic, and therefore he did it to take care of him:&mdash;That his being taken in the day-time on board, was plain there was no &s;ecret de&s;ign, nor harm infended to come to him:&mdash;And that when he parted with him at mr. Smith's, he behaved in a very mad manner, and took no leave <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">A Friend to both of them, at Bri&s;tol, who knew their mortal antipathy invited them once to dinner, in hopes to reconcile them, and &s;ays, That they parted that evening in &s;eeming Friend|&s;hip.&mdash;Captain Goodere's &s;on, who was heir to the Title, but being young at the untimely death of his father, did, when he was grown up, take the name of &s;ir John Dineley Goodere, and afterwards litigated with divers per&s;ons for part of the patrimony of his father and uncle, and &s;oon &s;pent what &s;mall &s;hare he recovered by it.&mdash;He afterwards went to Scotland, and &s;tudied phy|$ic there, becoming an $tinerant doctor, where he is now living: at his decea&s;e the Dineley and Goodere's family will be quite extinct</NOTE>.</P>
<P>In order to prove &s;ir John a lunatic, he called upon mrs. Gethens, to &s;ignify, That he had intimated to her &s;ome time before his intention of &s;ecuring &s;ir John as a luna|t$c; and that he propo&s;ed to her to have a g$rret for air, and other conveniencies; and that Mahony was to attend him, and to have five &s;hillings a week for his pains:&mdash;[Though mrs. Gethens, when called on, declared &s;he knew nothing of Mahony, nor of any &s;uch bargain.]&mdash;That the people
<PB N="43" REF="45">
on board knew of his coming a week before he came, to prevent his running out the e&s;tate; therefore, he intimated, that he mu&s;t be very &s;illy to bring a per&s;on to three hun|dred evidences to commit a vile act, where nathing can be kept a Secret above four hours.</P>
<P>The Captain likewi&s;e brought two young women to prove &s;ir John a lunatic; one of whom &s;aid, She believed him to be mad, becau&s;e he would get up in the middle of the night and di&s;turb all the &s;ervants: That &s;ometimes he would bu&s;y him&s;elf in hanging on the pot, &amp;c.</P>
<P>A Gentleman was called by Captain Good$re to his character; when being a&s;k|ed, Whether he knew &s;ir John to be any way mad$ or the like; decla$ed, That he was &s;o f$r from being a lunatic, that he had more &s;en&s;e than the whole family.&mdash;Sir John was al&s;o proved by mr. Smith to be in his perfect &s;en&s;e$, the hour before he was hurried away.</P>
<P>The evidence for the king being clear and &s;ull, the Jury, after a trial of nine hours, brought in their verdict, That the pri&s;oners were all GUILTY.</P>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1>
<PB N="44" REF="46">
<HEAD>An ACCOUNT of Capt. GOODERE's Behaviour a&s;ter Sentence of Death.</HEAD>
<P>WHEN he returned to Newgate, he went on foot, with a &s;carlet cloak on, and, as he pa&s;&s;ed along the &s;treets, he was very particular in making his obei&s;ance to the gentry and others of his acquaintance. After which his lady, who bears the charac|ter of a worthy gentlewoman, &s;pared no pains for his life, and petitioned that his &s;entence of death might be mitigated, or el&s;e changed into tran&s;portation or impri&s;onment. But &s;he not having &s;ucce&s;s in her application for mercy, his Friends de&s;ired him to turn his thoughts upon eternity. for that there was no hope of any favour from the higher pow|ers. <Q>And on the 8th of April, as a Me|mento Mori, his coffin was carried into his apartment in the gaol, with this in&s;cription, &startq;SAMUEL GOODERE, aged 53 years, who departed this life, April 15, 1741;&endq;</Q> at the &s;ight of which he was very much ca&s;t
<PB N="45" REF="47">
down, and became &s;orrowful; and then the rev. mr. We&s;ton, curate of St. Peter's, and mr. Penro&s;e, rector of St. Wa&s;bro&s;e, two worthy and learned divines, were de&s;ired to attend him, and prepare him for another world. They &s;eriou&s;ly pre&s;&s;ed him to the acknowledgment of his crime; but he per|&s;i&s;ted that he had no intention to murder his brother, but only to bring him from tho&s;e meafures he was pur&s;uing, &s;o highly inju|rious to the family.</P>
<P>Several Sermons were preached to him to bring him to a &s;en&s;e of religion; and the &s;unday before he died, the rev. mr. Rogers, rector of St. Peter's and Ocle, in Hereford|&s;hire, and an intimate friend of his, preach|ed from the following words: <Q>&startq;For if we believe that Je&s;us died, and ro&s;e again, even &s;o them al&s;o which &s;leep in Je&s;us will God bring with him. I. $he&s;&s;. iv. 14.&endq;</Q> Which was done in &s;uch a pathe|tic manner, that it drew tears from his eyes and mo&s;t of his audience.</P>
<P>At length the&s;e gentlemen, by the power and grace of their admonitions, &s;o molified his heart, that at la&s;t they prevailed over him, (being terrified with God's ju&s;tice, and encouraged by his mercies) and with tears and groans he confe&s;&s;ed the murder of his brother, and bitterly repented it; thanking tho&s;e godly divines for their charity, care, and zeal for his &s;oul, and be&s;ought them to pray to the Lord to forgive him and receive him into his ble&s;t abodes. And then he
<PB N="46" REF="48">
&s;pent mo&s;t of his time in prayer, &s;inging of p&s;alms, reading, meditation, and good di&s;|cour&s;es: his thoughts being wholly taken up with preparations to die: And it is hoped, that through the ble&s;&s;ing of God and the charitable a&s;&s;i&s;tance of the&s;e pious men, he was brought to a true repentance and abhor|rence of his atrocious crime.</P>
<P>Some days before he died, he earne&s;tly de&s;ired to partake of the Lord's Supper; but the mini&s;ter told him, he could not comply with his reque&s;t, until he had openly confe&s;&s;ed his crime, and declared him&s;elf to have truly repented of it.</P>
<P>He appeared very &s;orrowful, and could not refrain from tears, when he thought of his brother: His ingratitude to him, and the di&s;grace brought on his family, pre&s;ent|ed them&s;elwes alternately to his tortured mind, which gave him much unea&s;ine&s;s, and added to the agonies of his approaching end. He prayed for forgivene&s;s of God, and that mankind might learn, from his example, to re&s;train their pa&s;&s;ion, and not &s;uffer them&s;elves to be carried beyond the bounds of rea&s;on and humanity. He was much concerned he had not a more favour|able &s;entence pa&s;&s;ed upon him, or at lea&s;t, to die like a gentleman; but, at the &s;ame time, reflecting on his crimes, he acknowledged the ju&s;tice of the decree which the court had pa&s;&s;ed on him: And before he died, he took the &s;acrament with his lady, who de|parted
<PB N="47" REF="49">
out of the city of Bri&s;tol immediately afterwards.</P>
<P>On Wedne&s;day the 15th day of April, 1741, about eleven o'clock in the forenoon, captain Goodere was conveyed in a mourn|ing chariot, through the greate&s;t croud as ever was known in Bri&s;tol. An infinite number of people of all ranks were a&s;&s;em|bled at St. Michael's Hill, which was the plaee appointed for his and his $ellow &s;uf|ferers execution, to &s;ee them take their la&s;t farewell of this world; when the captain behaved with a becoming decency, and the tranquility of a &s;en&s;$ble man and a true penitent.</P>
<P>After &s;ome private di&s;cour&s;e with mr. Pen|ro&s;e, he confe&s;&s;ed the c$$me, and that it was the ju&s;tice of God that he &s;hould under|go th$t ignominous death; he be&s;ought the &s;pectators to pray for his &s;oul; he lamented his cruelty to his brother, and &s;aid, that his brother's cutting off the entail of the e&s;tate, to the prejudice of his family, had carried his re$entment beyond rea&s;on, and thereby brought him to this &s;hameful end; he ex|horted them to take example by him; and &s;olemnly freed his lady, and other relations, from being any way acce&s;&s;ary, or acquainted with his intention to murder his brother. He then joined in prayers with mr. Penro&s;e, and, after having &s;ung a p&s;alm, he embrac|ed and thanked the mini&s;ter for his offices in his behalf; and, in a mo&s;t tender manner,
<PB N="48" REF="50">
took leave of his acquaintance about him; and was heard to &s;ay, at &s;everal different times, Lord do not reward me according to my de&s;erts.</P>
<P>When he came to the fatal tree, and &s;aw Mahony and White, he embraced them with very great tenderne&s;s, and was much grieved to think he was the means of bring|ing them to that untimely end. And, ac|cording to his de&s;ire, when he dropped his handkerchief, which was the fignal, he was turned off; whil&s;t many of the &s;pecta|tors &s;ent up their prayers and good wi&s;hes for his eternal welfare.</P>
<P>After he had hung above an hour and a quarter he was cut down, and his corp&s;e was carried in a hear&s;e back to Newgate, and it lay there all night, by order of the ma|gi&s;trates, in order to prevent any art being made u$e of to bring him to life; and the next day he was carried in a hear&s;e, with &s;ix hor&s;es, to be buried in Hereford among&s;t his Ance&s;tors.</P>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
